What herbs fit the mood, how do I feel, how do they feel, and of course, how do they look. Many of the recipes for Supernatural Cafe were developed this way initially, as well as those in our online shop. I start from feel and then whittle it down with details based on who it’s for and where it’s going. A snapshot of the creative process, which is where I most love to be. And that’s exactly what the next chapters are about.

Buckwheat Cacao Cookies with Adaptogens, featuring the grain-free flour that doubles as an immune supplement. 🍪⚖️🫠 #BBHPartner (If that headline doesn’t check all of your boxes …!)

This month, I worked out a new recipe with @bigboldhealth’s unparalleled Himalayan Tartary Buckwheat flour — for the darkest, cacao-rich, molasses-sweetened v/gf/etc cookies I’ve ever had. And having them I am (we’re on batch two of the month already).

A moment for the flour, which is actually an organic, grain-free super nutritious seed that contains 100x the spectrum of benefits as common buckwheat. In addition to #polyphenols, it’s full of the protein, #prebiotics, antioxidants, and resistant starch that earn it a superfood categorization.

Research shows that baking with Himalayan Tartary Buckwheat flour actually enhances levels of certain polyphenols. (Aside: How many flour brands are doing studies on their ingredients? Love.) So, let’s do that. 🔹Link and code for 20% off Big Bold Health’s immuno-rejuvenating supplements are always in my bio.🔹

RECIPE:
Ingredients (makes 12)
2 C Himalayan Tartary Buckwheat Flour
⅓ C cacao or unsweetened cocoa powder
1 TBSP baking powder
3/4 C molasses
1 C (2 sticks) unsalted plant-based butter, butter, or ghee (room temp)
1¼ C chocolate chips or 100% cacao
1 tsp espresso, coffee, or herbal coffee (I used the latter)
Sea salt (Maldon ideally, for sprinkling)
Optional:
Powdered herb of choice to bake in (I used a homemade Reishi blend)
Powdered herb of choice for sprinkling (I used mucuna pruriens)
Directions
Preheat oven to 375°. Line a baking sheet w/ parchment paper.
Whisk dry ingredients; set aside.
Use an electric mixer (or not) to beat molasses and butter in a large bowl until light and fluffy. Add dry ingredients and beat until no dry spots remain. Add chocolate and coffee until fully blended.
Place cookies on baking sheet and sprinkle with a little bit of salt and anything else you like. Bake for about 12–15 minutes. Let cool slightly on sheet, then transfer to a wire rack.

“On the latest episode of Plant-Based, Rachelle Robinett, a registered herbalist and the founder of @ursupernatural, shows us how to make a refreshing alcohol-free mojito packed with mood-boosting ingredients. This delicious citrusy drink perfectly replicates the immaculate vacay vibes of a White Lotus beachside resort—minus all of the drama, of course.

“When adding greens to drink recipes, Robinett likes to rely on dense, liquid forms of spirulina, chlorella, and chlorophyll. “We get electrolytes, liver support, minerals and vitamins, and certain phytonutrients—plant compounds that help support the function of our liver—[from] greens,” Robinett says. In this recipe, she opts for spirulina, a saltwater-derived blue-green algae that not only gives this beverage a vibrant green color but also adds tons of liver-boosting benefits (plus vitamins, minerals, immune health support, and potent antioxidants). Spirulina also contains the essential amino acid tryptophan, a precursor to serotonin, which can help boost your mood and promote more restful sleep.” — @iamwellandgood

Liver-supportive mojito mocktail recipe
Yields 1 serving

In our early 30’s we begin to lose collagen. While we can’t stop that natural process we can slow it down, and support production, by supplying our systems with the necessary building blocks for making what it needs. (Those, btw, can be entirely plant-based.) Collagen is made from the amino acids glycine, lysine, and proline. Glycine needs B vitamins for its synthesis and side note, glycine can be great for sleep support. Lysine is essential, which means it’s not produced in the body and has to come from an outside source. Vitamin C is also integral. While we need all three of these amino acids to produce collagen, vitamin deficiencies can roadblock the process. Look to herbs like Nettle, He Shou Wu, Horsetail, and Gynostemma for some of these nutrients, supplement smartly (and test for any nutrient deficiencies), eat as well as life allows, and remember, as always, gut health.

Botanical Buckwheat Cookies with ginger, pine, and bergamot. (Highly recommended for your next hike, picnic, or backyard BBQ!) #bigboldhealthpartner
Summer baking is debatable except in the case of these cookies which require just a few minutes of heat, and feature such a special combination of ingredients from nature that they both taste like being outside, and are perfect for eating in the wild.
Imagine the bouquet of flavors from forest-y pine nuts, bright ginger, earthy buckwheat, and the musky floral of bergamot, which I harvested from my garden for the role of confetti here.

Central of course is @bigboldhealth’s Himalayan Tartary Buckwheat flour—the ingredient for summer rejuvenation that also supports soil health. BBH works with a cooperative of small family farms that use organic methods of growing, and they’re committed to understanding the soil + plant + immune system connection of the flour.

This recipe is vegan and gluten-free without the need to modify, though you’re always welcome to customize. Simply swapping out the nuts and spices transforms these nuggets into something new, so perhaps keep this recipe around for Fall, and Winter too, not that I’m thinking about either of those seasons rn!

RECIPE
• .5 C coconut oil
• .3 C coconut sugar
• .2 C molasses
• 1.5 C Himalayan Tartary Buckwheat Flour*
• 2 tsp baking powder
• 2.5 TBSP ground ginger
• 1 tsp ground cinnamon
• .3 C pine nuts
• Baking sheet and parchment paper
• Optional: Dried flowers for topping
~
• Preheat oven to 350 F
• Mix coconut oil and sugar until creamy
• Stir in molasses
• Work in dry ingredients
• Fold in pine nuts
~
• On a parchment-paper lined baking sheet, roll small cookies into balls and flatten with fingers
• Bake for 8-10 min (until edges are brown and top is soft)
• Cool on a cookie sheet
• Decorate as you please
~
Enjoy outside!
